    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You have hit on a crucial distinction: if healthcare is strictly defined as a fundamental human right, then economic efficiency and market competition become secondary concerns to the moral obligation of providing care to all citizens. However, in practice, governments rarely have the unlimited resources to provide a perfect system regardless of cost, so the debate often shifts to how best to structure the bureaucracy to minimize waste while still fulfilling that right. Most modern societies attempt a middle ground by using market mechanisms to fund and deliver care, rather than viewing the government's role as solely a bureaucratic provider, which is why the \"inefficiency\" argument remains a valid point of contention even for those who support universal access.",
      "source": "target",
